## 2. Divergence Types – Operationalised

| Type | Definition | Example from this case study |
|------|------------|------------------------------|
| **Substantive** | Different facts, causal mechanisms, or quantitative estimates | Automation speed (gradual vs. exponential); productivity percentage ranges |
| **Normative** | Different value priorities, risk tolerances, or policy preferences | Regulation as brake vs. protection; social mobility pessimism vs. democratisation |
| **Didactic** | Different explanation styles, examples, or structuring – same underlying claim | One model uses bullet points, another uses prose; same conclusion on dual training |
| **Architectural** | Different underlying model assumptions (e.g., US‑centric vs. EU‑centric training data) | Claude/DeepSeek more critical of EU AI Act; Gemini more supportive |

**Decision rule for synthesis:**  
Only substantive and normative divergences are carried forward. Didactic differences are ignored. Architectural differences are documented (as above) but not arithmetically merged.

